
# 🚀 Nmap – Scan Timing and Performance

Optimizing scan speed and accuracy in Nmap is critical when dealing with different network conditions, stealth requirements, and large-scale environments. This guide explains **Timing Templates, Parallelism, Host Group Sizes, Host Timeout, Scan Delay, and Packet Rate**—including **why, when, and where to use them**, along with practical examples.

---

# 📌 1. Timing Templates (`-T`)

## 🔍 What it is

Timing templates are predefined profiles that control multiple performance-related settings at once.

## ⚙️ Options

| Template | Name       | Description              |
| -------- | ---------- | ------------------------ |
| `-T0`    | Paranoid   | Extremely slow, stealthy |
| `-T1`    | Sneaky     | Very slow                |
| `-T2`    | Polite     | Reduces bandwidth usage  |
| `-T3`    | Normal     | Default                  |
| `-T4`    | Aggressive | Faster scans             |
| `-T5`    | Insane     | Very fast, less reliable |

## ✅ Why use it

* Simplifies performance tuning
* Balances speed vs stealth vs accuracy

## 📅 When to use

* Use `-T0` / `-T1` → Avoid detection (IDS/IPS)
* Use `-T3` → General scanning
* Use `-T4` → Faster results in stable networks
* Use `-T5` → Only in trusted/local networks

## 🌍 Where helpful

* Penetration testing
* Internal audits
* Bug bounty reconnaissance

## 💡 Example

```bash
nmap -T4 192.168.1.1
```

➡️ Faster scan with reasonable accuracy

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 📌 2. Parallelism (`--min-parallelism`, `--max-parallelism`)

## 🔍 What it is

Controls how many probes (packets) Nmap sends simultaneously.

## ✅ Why use it

* Increase speed with higher parallelism
* Reduce network congestion with lower values

## 📅 When to use

* High parallelism → Fast networks
* Low parallelism → Slow or unstable networks

## 🌍 Where helpful

* Large enterprise networks
* Cloud scanning environments

## 💡 Example

```bash
nmap --min-parallelism 10 --max-parallelism 50 192.168.1.0/24
```

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 📌 3. Host Group Sizes (`--min-hostgroup`, `--max-hostgroup`)

## 🔍 What it is

Defines how many hosts Nmap scans in parallel as a group.

## ✅ Why use it

* Larger groups → Faster scanning
* Smaller groups → Better control and accuracy

## 📅 When to use

* Large networks → Increase size
* Sensitive environments → Decrease size

## 🌍 Where helpful

* Corporate network sweeps
* Data center audits

## 💡 Example

```bash
nmap --min-hostgroup 32 --max-hostgroup 128 10.0.0.0/16
```

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 📌 4. Host Timeout (`--host-timeout`)

## 🔍 What it is

Specifies how long Nmap waits before giving up on a host.

## ✅ Why use it

* Prevents wasting time on unresponsive systems

## 📅 When to use

* Networks with many offline hosts
* Time-limited scans

## 🌍 Where helpful

* Internet-wide scanning
* Bug bounty programs

## 💡 Example

```bash
nmap --host-timeout 30s 192.168.1.0/24
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 📌 5. Scan Delay (`--scan-delay`, `--max-scan-delay`)

## 🔍 What it is

Adds delay between sending packets to avoid detection or throttling.

## ✅ Why use it

* Evade IDS/IPS
* Handle rate-limited services

## 📅 When to use

* Firewalled networks
* Intrusion detection environments

## 🌍 Where helpful

* Red team operations
* Stealth reconnaissance

## 💡 Example

```bash
nmap --scan-delay 1s 192.168.1.1
```

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

# 📌 6. Packet Rate (`--min-rate`, `--max-rate`)

## 🔍 What it is

Controls the number of packets sent per second.

## ✅ Why use it

* Fine-tune scan speed
* Prevent network overload

## 📅 When to use

* High-speed scans → Increase rate
* Fragile networks → Decrease rate

## 🌍 Where helpful

* High-performance environments
* WAN vs LAN tuning

## 💡 Example

```bash
nmap --min-rate 1000 --max-rate 5000 192.168.1.0/24
nmap -sS -T2 --scan-delay 500ms --max-rate 50 target.com
```

------------------------------------------------------

# ⚖️ Best Practices

* Start with `-T3` (default), then adjust
* Combine options carefully (avoid over-optimization)
* Test settings on small targets first
* Avoid `-T5` on unstable networks
* Monitor network impact during scans

